<section class="seo-content">
  <h2>How to play Connections</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>You are shown a grid of sixteen words that secretly belong to four hidden groups of four.</li>
    <li>Tap four words you think share a connection, then press Submit to test your group.</li>
    <li>Guess correctly and the group locks in, color-coded by difficulty from yellow (easiest) to purple (trickiest).</li>
    <li>Guess wrong and you lose one of your four attempts &mdash; the game tells you when you are just "one away."</li>
    <li>Use Shuffle to rearrange the tiles for a fresh look, and Deselect to clear your current pick.</li>
    <li>Solve all four groups before you run out of mistakes to win the day.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Tips &amp; strategy</h2>
  <p>
    Resist the urge to submit your very first idea. The puzzle is built on overlap: several words will
    look like they belong to more than one category, and the trap groups are placed there on purpose.
    Start with the connection you are most certain about, but double-check that none of those four words
    fits an even tighter group elsewhere.
  </p>
  <p>
    A good habit is to mentally sort all sixteen words before you tap anything, then solve the groups you
    are surest of first &mdash; usually the straightforward yellow and green sets. That clears away decoys and
    makes the harder blue and purple connections fall into place. If you are "one away," swap out the single
    word you are least confident about rather than rebuilding the whole group from scratch.
  </p>

  <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
  <details>
    <summary>Is Connections free?</summary>
    <p>Yes. It is a free daily Connections-style word game with no account, no app, and no paywall. Just open the page and start grouping.</p>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>When does the daily puzzle reset?</summary>
    <p>A new set of sixteen words goes live once a day. Come back tomorrow for the next grid, or play earlier puzzles in the <a href="/connections/archive">archive</a>.</p>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>How is this different from NYT Connections?</summary>
    <p>It is the same grouping concept &mdash; sixteen words, four hidden categories, four mistakes allowed &mdash; but ours is free, runs in any browser, and keeps a daily leaderboard. It is made by the team behind a science newsletter and is not affiliated with the New York Times, so it is a free Connections alternative.</p>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Can I play past puzzles?</summary>
    <p>Yes. The <a href="/connections/archive">Connections archive</a> lets you go back and solve grids from previous days any time.</p>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Do I need an account?</summary>
    <p>No sign-up required. Your progress saves in your browser, and you only type a nickname if you want to land on the daily leaderboard.</p>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>How many mistakes do I get?</summary>
    <p>You are allowed four mistakes. Use them all before solving every group and the puzzle reveals the answers, so guess thoughtfully and lock in your safest groups first.</p>
  </details>

